### Wave 3: Engine Design
Depends on Wave 2 rule extraction.
- [ ] data-model — Define all Rust types (structs, enums, field types) from extracted rules
- [ ] computation-pipeline — Design ordered pipeline steps with input/output types per step
- [ ] algorithms — Specify algorithms with exact arithmetic (BigRational fractions, integer centavos)
- [ ] test-vectors — Write 15-20 test vectors with expected outputs covering all major scenarios
- [ ] invariants — Define invariants that must hold for any valid input/output pair

### Wave 4: Bridge Contract
Depends on Wave 3 data model.
- [ ] wasm-export-signature — Define exported function names, parameter types, return types
- [ ] serde-wire-format — Document exact JSON serialization rules (booleans, numbers, nulls, enums, unknown fields)
- [ ] error-contract — Specify error shapes returned by WASM functions
- [ ] initialization-patterns — Document initSync vs init for Node.js vs browser

### Wave 5: Frontend Data Model + UI Design
Depends on Wave 3 data model and Wave 4 bridge contract.
- [ ] typescript-types — Map every Rust struct/enum to TypeScript interface/union (exact field names)
- [ ] zod-schemas — Write strict Zod schemas matching serde wire format (no coercion, null not undefined)
- [ ] wizard-steps — Define form step structure, fields per step, conditional visibility
- [ ] results-view — Define results display components and data mapping
- [ ] shared-components — Identify reusable form widgets (money input, date input, enum select, etc.)
- [ ] design-system — Choose palette, typography, component library, spacing, visual direction
- [ ] auth-flow — Specify authentication methods, sign-in/sign-up page layout, confirmation flow, error states, post-auth redirect
- [ ] landing-page — Specify unauthenticated user experience at `/`: sign-in/sign-up CTA, product description, auth-aware conditional rendering
- [ ] route-table — Complete route registry: every path, component, and auth requirement (public vs authenticated). Every route file MUST be registered.
- [ ] env-configuration — List all required env vars, .env.local.example contents, graceful error handling when vars are missing (no unhandled throws)
- [ ] database-migrations — Specify migration sequence, idempotency rules (IF NOT EXISTS, CREATE OR REPLACE), no duplicate table creation across migrations
- [ ] navigation — Auth-aware sidebar/header: what unauthenticated users see vs authenticated users, mobile nav, active state
- [ ] component-wiring-map — For every component, specify: which route/page/tab/dialog renders it, how user navigates there from home screen, what triggers it (for modals), and where props come from. No orphans allowed.

### Wave 6: Synthesis
Depends on all previous waves. **Strict internal dependency order — do NOT skip ahead.**
- [ ] spec-draft — Assemble all findings into docs/plans/{{SPEC_FILENAME}}.md with every section fully written (no empty sections, no placeholder content)
- [ ] placeholder-validation — **HARD GATE.** Scan entire spec line-by-line for banned patterns (TODO, TBD, FIXME, XXX, bracket placeholders, empty sections, deferral phrases). MUST return PASS (zero matches) before proceeding. If FAIL: create new aspects to resolve each gap.
- [ ] completeness-audit — Verify every feature/component/algorithm has implementation-ready detail: exact types, exact behavior, exact edge cases, exact error handling. Per-feature PASS/FAIL. If any FAIL: create aspects to fill gaps.
- [ ] cross-layer-consistency — Verify field names, types, enums, nullability match across Rust ↔ JSON ↔ TypeScript ↔ Zod
- [ ] spec-review — Final review: can a developer build the ENTIRE product — every feature fully functional, every UI element wired, every edge case handled — from this spec alone without asking a single clarifying question?

